    "narrative_summary": "The BRCA1 nonsense variant E445* (c.1333G>T, p.Glu445*) creates a premature stop codon in exon 11 and is implicated in hereditary breast and ovarian cancer susceptibility. Clinical databases and large\u2011scale variant catalogs classify this change as pathogenic; the Asian BRCA1/2 variant compendium explicitly lists p.Glu445* among pathogenic alleles [PMC10098510] and a supplementary ClinVar\u2011derived table records it as a stop\u2011gain pathogenic variant [PMC8860097]. No studies in the provided set report a benign or likely\u2011benign interpretation. Functional data are not presented in the extracted evidence; one study notes the mutation generates a TAG termination codon but does not assess its biological impact [PMC10471768]. Population surveys show the variant has been observed in a Caucasian individual from Spain (single occurrence) [PMC9907816] and is reported in Caucasian cohorts, yet it was absent from more than 30,000 Chinese hereditary breast\u2011ovarian cancer patients, indicating an ethnic\u2011specific distribution rather than a universal founder effect [PMC6617753]. No computational predictive scores are provided in the extracted material. Taken together, the available evidence consistently supports a pathogenic role for BRCA1\u202fE445* in cancer predisposition, with no contradictory findings, and suggests its relevance may be limited to certain populations.",
    "structured_summary": {
        "overall_pathogenicity": "pathogenic",
        "pathogenicity_counts": {
            "supports benignity": 0,
            "supports pathogenicity": 2,
            "uncertain": 0
        },
        "conflicting_evidence": false
    },
